prompt:
Use Three.js to implement a 3D avocado slicing interactive tool. Load the Avocado.glb model; the user can define a cutting plane and perform slice operations (simulated with clipping planes).

[Three.js Import (must follow strictly)]
Add the following importmap in <head>, and import via ES Module in <script type="module">:
<script type="importmap">
{ "imports": {
    "three": "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.170.0/build/three.module.js",
    "three/addons/": "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.170.0/examples/jsm/"
} }
</script>
<script type="module">
import * as THREE from 'three';
import { GLTFLoader } from 'three/addons/loaders/GLTFLoader.js';
import { OrbitControls } from 'three/addons/controls/OrbitControls.js';
// Your code here
</script>

[Model Loading]
(1) Load assets/Avocado.glb using GLTFLoader;
(2) Scale to appropriate size (scale ~30-50), center in scene;
(3) After loading, set window.__3D_STATE__.modelLoaded = true;

[OrbitControls]
(4) Use OrbitControls to inspect the model;

[Cutting Line Drawing]
(5) User presses and drags on canvas to draw a cutting line (visible red line via HTML Canvas overlay or CSS line);
(6) Cutting line remains visible after mouse release;
(7) Compute the 3D cutting plane normal from the cutting line's screen position and direction;

[Cutting Plane Visualization]
(8) Display a semi-transparent cutting plane in the 3D scene (PlaneGeometry, semi-transparent red 0xff0000, opacity=0.3), corresponding to the on-screen cutting line;
(9) Cutting plane large enough to cover the model (e.g. 2x2);

[Slice Operation]
(10) Slice button (id="sliceBtn"): click to perform slicing;
(11) Use THREE.js clippingPlanes to apply the cutting plane as a material clip plane;
(12) After slicing, the model is split in two along the cutting plane. Implementation: clone the model, apply a forward clipping plane to one copy and a reverse clipping plane to the other, separate the two halves slightly in opposite directions (0.2 units each);
(13) renderer.localClippingEnabled = true must be enabled;
(14) Each slice increments sliceCount += 1;

[Reset]
(15) Reset button (id="resetBtn"): clear all cuts, restore original model, reset sliceCount to zero;

[HUD Display]
(16) Top-left HUD:
  - Slice count (id="sliceCount")
  - Cutting plane normal (id="planeNormal", shows x, y, z)
  - Model visibility (id="visibility")

[Visual Effects]
(17) Scene background: light yellow (0xFFF8E1);
(18) Soft AmbientLight + DirectionalLight;
(19) Optional: add cross-section color effect at the cut face (stencil or simple color plane);

[State Exposure (required)]
Update window.__3D_STATE__ every frame:
  - modelLoaded: boolean (whether model has finished loading)
  - sliceCount: number (number of slices performed)
  - planeNormal: { x: number, y: number, z: number } | null (current cutting plane normal)
  - planeVisible: boolean (whether cutting plane is visible)
  - modelVisible: boolean (whether model is visible)
  - clippingEnabled: boolean (whether clipping is enabled)

Output a single self-contained HTML file. Place the file and the assets/ folder in the same directory; serve via a local HTTP server.
